TI  - ASH PHYSICAL CHARACTERISTICS AFFECTS DIFFERENTLY SOIL HYDROLOGY AND EROSION SUBPROCESSES
T2  - LAND DEGRADATION & DEVELOPMENT
AB  - After slash-and-burn agriculture, topsoil becomes covered by ash layers of various colors. The different colored ashes have particular properties that may affect the hydro-erosional processes on hillslopes in different ways. In the present study, the effects of black and gray ashes on the hydro-erosional processes were examined in the context of slash-and-burn, and the soil erosion subprocesses responsible for soil loss were identified. Black and gray ashes were collected in the field after two slash-and-burn fires. The experiment was conducted in wettable, clay-textured, brown oxisols. In the laboratory, the ash was spread carefully by hand over a plot of 0.14 m(2). Simulated rainfall was discharged from a height of 6 m from the central plot for a period of 30 min with a rainfall intensity of 58 mm h(-1). Gray ash reduced infiltration five times more than black ash and four times more than bare soil. The runoff coefficient showed black ash with minor runoff of similar to 7%, bare soil displayed intermediate runoff of similar to 12%, and gray ash exhibited the major runoff coefficient of 19%. Gray ash generated six and three and a half times more sediment than black ash and bare soil, respectively. This study determined that soil hydrology is affected more by ash cover than soil loss. Black ash protects against soil erosion and improves soil water infiltration; gray ash dramatically changes the topsoil hydrology and interill erosion processes; and bare soil and soil cover with different ash colors lose soil through different erosion subprocesses. Copyright (C) 2017 John Wiley & Sons, Ltd.
