ED  - Prieto, R
TI  - ISN'T THERE AN ALTERNATIVE TO DEFORESTATION IN AMAZONAS?
T2  - AMAZON BASIN: PLANT LIFE, WILDLIFE AND ENVIRONMENT
AB  - Deforestation of the Brazilian Amazon rainforests is more than a regional issue, for the impacts spread further away than the country's borders. Forests clear-cut by slash-and-burn practices release about 20% of all human-induced carbon emissions, contributing to Greenhouse Gas (GHG) effects. The main deforestation drivers are logging followed by agriculture and ranching driven by economical forces. However, Amazonas, the largest state in the country, still has 97% of its area covered with primitive rainforests, and there are alternatives for its sustainable development, like the improvement of the current high-tech industrial model of Manaus and trading agreements for preserved forests and also for lesser GHG emissions from deforestation versus development credit. Nevertheless, the governmental, private and public sectors active participation is required for these proposals to come into being and long-lasting.
